{
  "text": "Zigzag channel is a kind of passive mixing with planar structure, and is particularly convenient for microfluidic mixing because it is control-free and easy to fabricate. Different studies of microfluidic mixing with a zigzag channel have been reported [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . For example, Mengeaud et al. provided a theoretical study on mixing with a zigzag channel using Navier-Stokes equation and diffusion-convection equation in the steady state form for different zigzag ratios of channel width and periodic step distance [CITATION_6] . Ren et al. developed a numerical model accounting for the interactions of throughflow, crossflow and material dispersion by diffusion and convection in a rotational platforms, and the simulation results were found match to the experimental results at two selected rotation speeds [CITATION_7] . To the best of the authors' knowledge, this work first provides experimental evidence showing the relationship between the zigzag angle and mixing performance in a stationary zigzag channel. Microfluidic mixing with six different zigzag angles is investigated with a 1000-fold span of Reynolds number from 0.309 to 309. An image-based method is utilized for evaluating the performance of the mixing.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "99894519",
    "[CITATION_2]": "115016910",
    "[CITATION_3]": "205913807",
